gin this work with the Flint Neighborhood in Fall River and the Acushnet Avenue Neighborhood in New Bedford, sharing expertise and efficiencies to get the job done. Projects and programs will include:\n<ul>\n 	<li>Open space development and transformation of brownfields and derelict vacant lots into community assets</li>\n 	<li>Stewardship, civic pride and celebration</li>\n 	<li>Youth development through leadership, job readiness and skill building</li>\n 	<li>Green job training and career development</li>\n 	<li>Food security and improving access to healthy food through community gardens and farmers markets</li>\n</ul>\nThe need for a Groundwork presence in Fall River and New Bedford is abundantly clear; while many nonprofits exist in each community, those organizations are oriented predominantly as service providers to vulnerable and at-risk populations. While a small number of community development corporations exist in the region, they are focused on particular geographies within each community, as opposed to Groundworks eventual citywide scope. There also appears to be lack of an entity to support a more comprehensive project and programmatic response to the intertwined and intractable environmental, economic and social injustices on the ground.\n<h2></h2>\n&nbsp;\n\n</div>\n\";s:10:\"margin_top\";s:0:\"\";s:17:\"margin_top_medium\";s:0:\"\";s:21:\"margin_top_responsive\";s:0:\"\";s:13:\"margin_bottom\";s:0:\"\";s:20:\"margin_bottom_medium\";s:0:\"\";s:24:\"margin_bottom_responsive\";s:0:\"\";s:11:\"margin_left\";s:0:\"\";s:18:\"margin_left_medium\";s:0:\"\";s:22:\"margin_left_responsive\";s:0:\"\";s:12:\"margin_right\";s:0:\"\";s:19:\"margin_right_medium\";s:0:\"\";s:23:\"margin_right_responsive\";s:0:\"\";s:18:\"responsive_display\";s:0:\"\";s:18:\"visibility_display\";s:0:\"\";s:26:\"visibility_user_capability\";s:0:\"\";s:9:\"animation\";s:0:\"\";s:15:\"animation_delay\";s:3:\"0.0\";s:2:\"id\";s:0:\"\";s:5:\"class\";s:0:\"\";s:4:\"type\";s:9:\"rich-text\";