1 23:14:33','','Sitemap and website content? 2017','','inherit','open','closed','','sitemap-and-website-content-2017','','','2017-05-31 23:14:33','2017-05-31 23:14:33','',0,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/wp/../sites/groundworksouth/uploads/2017/05/Sitemap-and-website-content-2017.pptx',0,'attachment','application/vnd.openxmlformats-officedocument.presentationml.presentation',0),(19,3,'2017-06-01 01:33:53','2017-06-01 01:33:53','<h2>This summer we plan to launch our first program: Green Team. This will be a team of youth employees from Fall River and New Bedford working on physical space and community stewardship.</h2>\r\n<h2></h2>','Who we Are','','publish','closed','closed','','who-we-are','','','2017-06-01 01:51:46','2017-06-01 01:51:46','',4,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/?page_id=19',0,'page','',0),(20,3,'2017-06-01 01:09:31','2017-06-01 01:09:31','','Who we Are','','inherit','closed','closed','','19-revision-v1','','','2017-06-01 01:09:31','2017-06-01 01:09:31','',19,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/19-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(21,3,'2017-06-01 01:09:33','0000-00-00 00:00:00','','Auto Draft','','auto-draft','closed','closed','','','','','2017-06-01 01:09:33','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/?page_id=21',0,'page','',0),(22,3,'2017-06-01 01:47:22','2017-06-01 01:47:22','\n<p><a href=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/home-page/who-we-are/mission-statement\">Mission Statement</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/home-page/who-we-are/why-fall-river-and-new-bedford\">Fall River &amp; New Bedford</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/home-page/who-we-are/history\">History</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/home-page/who-we-are/staff-and-board\">Staff &amp; Board</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/home-page/what-we-do/our-stories\">Our Stories</a></p>\n	<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h1 style=\"text-align: left;\">STAFF</h1>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><img src=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/uploads/2017/06/P24-240x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"240\" height=\"300\" /></p>\n<h3><strong>Executive Director:</strong> Maura Ramsey</h3>\n<p>Maura has been with GWSC since March 2017. Sheis extremely passionate about furthering social, economic, racial, and environmental justice in our society through community focused leadership development. Prior to accepting the Executive Director position with GWSC, Maura worked at Mother\'s Out Front as the Massachusetts Lead Organizer, a non-profit that works to mobilize mothers, grandmothers and caregivers to have their voices heard as they advocate for a healthy climate for their children. She was also the Director of the South Street Youth Center, a non-profit located on the premises of a Boston Housing Authority development where she developed all programming and outreach to expand the youth center from onesmall drop-in program to a multi-service space that engaged, residents, neighbors, non-profits, city programs and state based stakeholder to respond to create the changes the community wanted.</p>\n	<hr />\n<h1 style=\"text-align: left;\">BOARD</h1>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><img src=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/uploads/2017/06/me-300x226.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"281\" height=\"212\" /></p>\n<h3><strong>Chair:</strong> Mike Coughlin</h3>\n<p>Michael Coughlin, MS, has been a public health professional at the state and local level since 1992. He is the Outreach and Education Coordinator for Greater Fall River Partners for a Healthier Community and an Adjunct Instructor in Human Services and Psychology at Bristol Community College. He also serves as a Site Visitor for the national Public Health Accreditation Board. Michael retired as the Accreditation Manager in the Office of the Commissioner in the MA Department of Public Health (MDPH) in June 2015. He previously served as the Local Public Health Manager in the Emergency Preparedness Bureau at MDPH. He served as the Director of Health and Human Services for the City of Fall River, MA from 2004-2008.</p>\n<h3></h3>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3><strong>Vice Chair:</strong> Ray Holberger</h3>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3><strong>Secretary:</strong> Eric Andrade</h3>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><img src=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/uploads/2017/06/emerging-leader-head-shot-225x300.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" /></p>\n<h3><strong>Treasurer:</strong> Brian Pastori</h3>\n<p>Brian Pastori has lived in New Bedford since 2004 and is a founding board member of Groundwork SouthCoast. Brian is the Deputy Director of the Community Economic Development Center (CEDC). He has worked at the CEDC since 2005 promoting asset development, neighborhood pride, and skill building in New Bedford with a particular focus on the Acushnet Avenue Neighborhood. Brians work is guided by a commitment to social and economic justice with the goal of building toward equity for oppressed communities.</p>\n<h1></h1>\n	<hr />\n<h1 style=\"text-align: left;\">MEMBERS</h1>\n<p>Jan De Silva</p>\n<p>Amy Blanchette</p>\n','Staff and Board','','publish','closed','closed','','staff-and-board','','','2017-06-04 19:23:22','2017-06-04 19:23:22','',19,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/?page_id=22',0,'page','',0),(23,3,'2017-06-02 17:09:48','2017-06-02 17:09:48','Welcome to your staging site for 48in48. This is the site where you will input your website content, build your menus and upload documents. Here are a few links you might need as you are using this site:\n<ul>\n 	<li><a href=\"../wp-admin\">Login Link</a></li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n\n<section class=\"content-section parallax padding-small\" data-velocity=\".8\">\n<div class=\"container entry-content\">\n\nThe mission of the Groundwork Southcoastis to bring about the sustained regeneration, improvement, and management of the physical environment by developing community-based partnerships that empower people, businesses, and organizations to promote environmental, economic, and social well-being.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n</div>\n</section><section id=\"profiles-news\" class=\"content-section\">\n<div class=\"container\">Thank you to our Sponsors and Supporters:</div>\n<div class=\"container\">The National Park Service/ City of Fall River/ City of New Bedford/ Bristol County Workforce Investment</div>\n</section>','Home Page','','inherit','closed','closed','','4-autosave-v1','','','2017-06-02 17:09:48','2017-06-02 17:09:48','',4,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/4-autosave-v1',0,'revision','',0),(24,3,'2017-06-01 01:25:14','2017-06-01 01:25:14','Welcome to your staging site for 48in48. This is the site where you will input your website content, build your menus and upload documents. Here are a few links you might need as you are using this site:\r\n<ul>\r\n 	<li><a href=\"../wp-admin\">Login Link</a></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<section class=\"content-section parallax padding-small\" data-velocity=\".8\">\r\n<div class=\"container entry-content\">\r\n\r\nThe mission of the Groundwork Southcoastis to bring about the sustained regeneration, improvement, and management of the physical environment by developing community-based partnerships that empower people, businesses, and organizations to promote environmental, economic, and social well-being.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n</section><section id=\"profiles-news\" class=\"content-section\">\r\n<div class=\"container\"></div>\r\n</section>','Home Page','','inherit','closed','closed','','4-revision-v1','','','2017-06-01 01:25:14','2017-06-01 01:25:14','',4,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/4-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(25,3,'2017-06-01 01:33:53','2017-06-01 01:33:53','<h2>OUR MISSION</h2>\r\nThe mission of Groundwork Southcoast(GWSC) is to bring about the sustained regeneration, improvement and management of the physical environment by developing community-based partnerships that empower people, businesses and organizations to promote environmental, economic and social well-being.\r\n<h2>OUR ROLE</h2>\r\nGWSC is part of the <a href=\"http://groundworkusa.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><strong>Groundwork USA</strong></a> network of independent, not-for-profit, environmental organizationscalled Groundwork Trusts. Locally organized and controlled, Groundwork Trusts provide services focused on improving their communities environment, economy, and quality of life.\r\n\r\nEach Trust represents a strong partnership between government, business, foundations, community groups, and residents. Projects serve a common agenda and are designed to accomplish other goals, such as stewarding urban waterways, brown field reclamation, job training and environmental education. All projects and activities of Groundwork are carried out to leverage resources forresidents totransform their own communities.\r\n<h2>OUR HISTORY</h2>\r\nAs an outgrowth of a program developed by the National Park Service, the Groundwork programs in the U.S. evolved from a model developed in the U.K. The first Groundwork Trust was founded in 1982 in England to meet the needs to revitalize abandoned industrial sites in northern England. Since then, the Groundwork UK organization has grown into a network of fifty-two locally based groups. This committed network became a highly successful private-public-community partnership that combined all resources necessary to take abandoned, run-down areas and reclaim them as open spaces with an emphasis on recreation, beautification, and economic development. Currently, there are 50 \"Groundwork Trusts\" in the U.K.\r\n\r\nIn 1996, the National Park Service imported this successful program into three pilot communities, Bridgeport, CT., Lawrence, MA., and Providence, RI. Since that point in time, the program has expanded into more in-need cities.\r\n\r\n9 years agoa number of members local organizations, agencies, and individuals began to advocate for a trust in Fall River and in New Bedford. In time a small committee was formed to discuss the possibility of establishing a Groundwork Trust in south eastern Massachusetts. In 2016, through partnership of the National Park Service, Groundwork Lawrence, the city of Fall River and the City of New Bedford GWSCwas designated a Groundwork Trust. With this designation, the Groundwork Southcoast Steering Committee received funds and technical assistance from the NPS and EPA to prepare a Feasibility Study and Strategic Plan assessing whether or not Groundwork was appropriate for our community. The strategic plan was approved andan Executive Director was hired in Februaryof 2017.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis summer we plan to launch our first program: Green Team. This will be a team of youth employees from Fall River and New Bedford working on physical space and community stewardship.','Who we Are','','inherit','closed','closed','','19-revision-v1','','','2017-06-01 01:33:53','2017-06-01 01:33:53','',19,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/19-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(26,3,'2017-06-01 01:46:44','2017-06-01 01:46:44','<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Staff:</span>\r\n\r\nExecutive Director:\r\n\r\nMaura Ramsey\r\n\r\n<span id=\"yui_3_16_0_ym19_1_1496281380157_3214\">Maura has been with GWSC since March 2017. Sheis extremely passionate about furthering social, economic, racial, and environmental justice in our society through community focused leadership development. Prior to accepting the Executive Director position with GWSC, Maura worked at Mother\'s Out Front as the Massachusetts Lead Organizer, a non-profit that works to mobilize mothers, grandmothers and caregivers to have their voices heard as they advocate for a healthy climate for their children. She was also the Director of the South Street Youth Center, a non-profit located on the premises of a Boston Housing Authority development where she developed all programming and outreach to expand the youth center from one</span><span id=\"yui_3_16_0_ym19_1_1496281380157_3221\">small drop-in program to a multi-service space that engaged, residents, neighbors, non-profits, city programs and state based stakeholder to respond to create the changes the community wanted.</span>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Board:</span>\r\n\r\nChair:\r\n\r\nMike Coughlin\r\n\r\nVice Chair:\r\n\r\nRay Holberger\r\n\r\nSecretary:\r\n\r\nEric Andrade\r\n\r\nTreasurer:\r\n\r\nBrian Pastori\r\n\r\nMembers:\r\n\r\nJan De Silva\r\n\r\nAmy Blanchette','Staff and Board','','inherit','closed','closed','','22-revision-v1','','','2017-06-01 01:46:44','2017-06-01 01:46:44','',22,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/22-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(27,3,'2017-06-01 01:48:49','2017-06-01 01:48:49','\n<p><a href=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/home-page/who-we-are/mission-statement\">Mission Statement</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/home-page/who-we-are/why-fall-river-and-new-bedford\">Fall River &amp; New Bedford</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/home-page/who-we-are/history\">History</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/home-page/who-we-are/staff-and-board\">Staff &amp; Board</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/home-page/what-we-do/our-stories\">Our Stories</a></p>\n	<h2>Mission Statement</h2>\n<hr />\n<p>The mission of Groundwork Southcoast (GWSC) is to bring about the sustained regeneration, improvement and management of the physical environment by developing community-based partnerships that empower people, businesses and organizations to promote environmental, economic and social well-being.</p>\n<h2>Who We Are</h2>\n<hr />\n<p>GWSC is part of the <a href=\"http://groundworkusa.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><strong>Groundwork USA</strong></a> network of independent, not-for-profit, environmental organizations called Groundwork Trusts. Locally organized and controlled, Groundwork Trusts provide services focused on improving their communities environment, economy, and quality of life.</p>\n<p>As a Groundwork Trust GWSC represents a strong partnership between government, business, foundations, community groups, and residents. Projects serve a common agenda and are designed to accomplish other goals, such as stewarding urban waterways, brown field reclamation, job training, environmental education, and developing future leaders through targeted youth leadership development. All projects and activities of Groundwork are carried out to leverage resources for residents to transform their own communities.</p>\n<h2>What We do</h2>\n<hr />\n<p>GWSC works collaboratively to develop current and future leadership to steward urban waterways and brownfields in environmental justice communities in south eastern Massachusetts.</p>\n','Mission Statement','','publish','closed','closed','','mission-statement','','','2017-06-04 19:51:51','2017-06-04 19:51:51','',19,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/?page_id=27',0,'page','',0),(28,3,'2017-06-01 01:48:49','2017-06-01 01:48:49','The mission of Groundwork Southcoast(GWSC) is to bring about the sustained regeneration, improvement and management of the physical environment by developing community-based partnerships that empower people, businesses and organizations to promote environmental, economic and social well-being.','Mission Statement','','inherit','closed','closed','','27-revision-v1','','','2017-06-01 01:48:49','2017-06-01 01:48:49','',27,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/27-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(29,3,'2017-06-01 01:49:45','2017-06-01 01:49:45','\n<p><a href=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/home-page/who-we-are/mission-statement\">Mission Statement</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/home-page/who-we-are/why-fall-river-and-new-bedford\">Fall River &amp; New Bedford</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/home-page/who-we-are/history\">History</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/home-page/who-we-are/staff-and-board\">Staff &amp; Board</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/home-page/what-we-do/our-stories\">Our Stories</a></p>\n	<h2>OUR HISTORY</h2>\n<hr />\n<p>As an outgrowth of a program developed by the National Park Service, the Groundwork programs in the U.S. evolved from a model developed in the U.K. The first Groundwork Trust was founded in 1982 in England to meet the needs to revitalize abandoned industrial sites in northern England. Since then, the Groundwork UK organization has grown into a network of fifty-two locally based groups. This committed network became a highly successful private-public-community partnership that combined all resources necessary to take abandoned, run-down areas and reclaim them as open spaces with an emphasis on recreation, beautification, and economic development. Currently, there are 50 \"Groundwork Trusts\" in the U.K.</p>\n<p>In 1996, the National Park Service imported this successful program into three pilot communities, Bridgeport, CT., Lawrence, MA., and Providence, RI. Since that point in time, the program has expanded into more in-need cities.</p>\n<p>9 years agoa number of members local organizations, agencies, and individuals began to advocate for a trust in Fall River and in New Bedford. In time a small committee was formed to discuss the possibility of establishing a Groundwork Trust in south eastern Massachusetts. In 2016, through partnership of the National Park Service, Groundwork Lawrence, the city of Fall River and the City of New Bedford- GWSCwas designated a Groundwork Trust. With this designation, the Groundwork Southcoast Steering Committee received funds and technical assistance from the NPS and EPA to prepare a Feasibility Study and Strategic Plan assessing whether or not Groundwork was appropriate for our community. The strategic plan was approved andan Executive Director was hired in Februaryof 2017.</p>\n','History','','publish','closed','closed','','history','','','2017-06-04 19:23:29','2017-06-04 19:23:29','',19,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/?page_id=29',0,'page','',0),(30,3,'2017-06-01 01:49:45','2017-06-01 01:49:45','<h2>OUR HISTORY</h2>\r\nAs an outgrowth of a program developed by the National Park Service, the Groundwork programs in the U.S. evolved from a model developed in the U.K. The first Groundwork Trust was founded in 1982 in England to meet the needs to revitalize abandoned industrial sites in northern England. Since then, the Groundwork UK organization has grown into a network of fifty-two locally based groups. This committed network became a highly successful private-public-community partnership that combined all resources necessary to take abandoned, run-down areas and reclaim them as open spaces with an emphasis on recreation, beautification, and economic development. Currently, there are 50 \"Groundwork Trusts\" in the U.K.\r\n\r\nIn 1996, the National Park Service imported this successful program into three pilot communities, Bridgeport, CT., Lawrence, MA., and Providence, RI. Since that point in time, the program has expanded into more in-need cities.\r\n\r\n9 years agoa number of members local organizations, agencies, and individuals began to advocate for a trust in Fall River and in New Bedford. In time a small committee was formed to discuss the possibility of establishing a Groundwork Trust in south eastern Massachusetts. In 2016, through partnership of the National Park Service, Groundwork Lawrence, the city of Fall River and the City of New Bedford GWSCwas designated a Groundwork Trust. With this designation, the Groundwork Southcoast Steering Committee received funds and technical assistance from the NPS and EPA to prepare a Feasibility Study and Strategic Plan assessing whether or not Groundwork was appropriate for our community. The strategic plan was approved andan Executive Director was hired in Februaryof 2017.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','History','','inherit','closed','closed','','29-revision-v1','','','2017-06-01 01:49:45','2017-06-01 01:49:45','',29,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/29-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(31,3,'2017-06-01 01:50:51','2017-06-01 01:50:51','<h2></h2>\n<h2></h2>','Who we Are','','inherit','closed','closed','','19-autosave-v1','','','2017-06-01 01:50:51','2017-06-01 01:50:51','',19,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/19-autosave-v1',0,'revision','',0),(32,3,'2017-06-01 01:50:53','2017-06-01 01:50:53','<h2></h2>\r\n<h2></h2>','Who we Are','','inherit','closed','closed','','19-revision-v1','','','2017-06-01 01:50:53','2017-06-01 01:50:53','',19,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/19-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(33,3,'2017-06-01 01:51:30','2017-06-01 01:51:30','\n<p><a href=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/home-page/who-we-are/mission-statement\">Mission Statement</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/home-page/who-we-are/why-fall-river-and-new-bedford\">Fall River &amp; New Bedford</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/home-page/who-we-are/history\">History</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/home-page/who-we-are/staff-and-board\">Staff &amp; Board</a></p>\n<p><a href=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/home-page/what-we-do/our-stories\">Our Stories</a></p>\n	<h1>Why Fall River and New Bedford</h1>\n<hr />\n<p>\nGWSC is the only community-based environmental organization in either city whos organizing focuses on: youth, residents, and other stakeholders in a grassroots-fueled, neighborhood-scale planning and redevelopment initiative aimed at reclaiming vacant, contaminated, underutilized and/or under-maintained land and waterways for community benefit. This whats next? agenda is a strong suit of the Groundwork model and, as such, holds great potential for these two cities as well as building the next generation of organizers and social justice leaders while recognizing the key role that the voice of youth has to play in this work alongside of adult and other marginalized residents.\n</p>\n','Why Fall River and New Bedford','','publish','closed','closed','','why-fall-river-and-new-bedford','','','2017-06-04 19:23:08','2017-06-04 19:23:08','',19,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/?page_id=33',0,'page','',0),(34,3,'2017-06-01 01:51:30','2017-06-01 01:51:30','<h2>OUR ROLE</h2>\r\nGWSC is part of the <a href=\"http://groundworkusa.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><strong>Groundwork USA</strong></a> network of independent, not-for-profit, environmental organizationscalled Groundwork Trusts. Locally organized and controlled, Groundwork Trusts provide services focused on improving their communities environment, economy, and quality of life.\r\n\r\nEach Trust represents a strong partnership between government, business, foundations, community groups, and residents. Projects serve a common agenda and are designed to accomplish other goals, such as stewarding urban waterways, brown field reclamation, job training and environmental education. All projects and activities of Groundwork are carried out to leverage resources forresidents totransform their own communities.\r\n<h2></h2>\r\n&nbsp;','Why Fall River and New Bedford','','inherit','closed','closed','','33-revision-v1','','','2017-06-01 01:51:30','2017-06-01 01:51:30','',33,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/33-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(35,3,'2017-06-01 01:51:46','2017-06-01 01:51:46','<h2>This summer we plan to launch our first program: Green Team. This will be a team of youth employees from Fall River and New Bedford working on physical space and community stewardship.</h2>\r\n<h2></h2>','Who we Are','','inherit','closed','closed','','19-revision-v1','','','2017-06-01 01:51:46','2017-06-01 01:51:46','',19,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/19-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(36,3,'2017-06-01 01:54:09','2017-06-01 01:54:09','Groundwork Southcoast\'s positioning statement, which indicates thespecific ways that mission statement will be implemented on the ground in Fall River and New Bedford, is:\n\nGroundwork Southcoast will collaborate with neighborhoods in Fall River and New Bedford to engage communities in the improvement and stewardship of parks, recreation and conserved natural areas, generate community pride, foster safer and healthier communities; and build diverse partnerships with residents and local businesses to direct and achieve these goals. Groundwork will begin this work with theFlint Neighborhood in Fall River and the Acushnet Avenue Neighborhood in New Bedford,\n\nsharing expertise and efficiencies to get the job done. Projects and programs will include:\n\n Open space development and transformation of brownfields and derelict vacant\n\nlots into community assets\n\n Stewardship, civic pride and celebration\n\n Youth development through leadership, job readiness and skill building\n\n Green job training and career development\n\n Food security and improving access to healthy food through community gardens\n\nand farmers markets\n\n3\n\nThe need for a Groundwork presence in Fall River and New Bedford is abundantly clear; while\n\nmany nonprofits exist in each community, those organizations are oriented predominantly as\n\nservice providers to vulnerable and at-risk populations. While a small number of community\n\ndevelopment corporations exist in the region, they are focused on particular geographies within\n\neach community, as opposed to Groundworks eventual citywide scope. There also appears to\n\nbe lack of an entity to support a more comprehensive project and programmatic response to\n\nthe intertwined and intractable environmental, economic and social injustices on the ground.\n<h2>OUR ROLE</h2>\nGWSC is part of the <a href=\"http://groundworkusa.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><strong>Groundwork USA</strong></a> network of independent, not-for-profit, environmental organizationscalled Groundwork Trusts. Locally organized and controlled, Groundwork Trusts provide services focused on improving their communities environment, economy, and quality of life.\n\nEach Trust represents a strong partnership between government, business, foundations, community groups, and residents. Projects serve a common agenda and are designed to accomplish other goals, such as stewarding urban waterways, brown field reclamation, job training and environmental education. All projects and activities of Groundwork are carried out to leverage resources forresidents totransform their own communities.\n<h2></h2>\n&nbsp;','Why Fall River and New Bedford','','inherit','closed','closed','','33-autosave-v1','','','2017-06-01 01:54:09','2017-06-01 01:54:09','',33,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/33-autosave-v1',0,'revision','',0),(37,3,'2017-06-01 01:55:03','2017-06-01 01:55:03','Groundwork Southcoast\'s positioning statement, which indicates thespecific ways that mission statement will be implemented on the ground in Fall River and New Bedford, is:\r\n\r\nGroundwork Southcoast will collaborate with neighborhoods in Fall River and New Bedford to engage communities in the improvement and stewardship of parks, recreation and conserved natural areas, generate community pride, foster safer and healthier communities; and build diverse partnerships with residents and local businesses to direct and achieve these goals. Groundwork will begin this work with the Flint Neighborhood in Fall River and the Acushnet Avenue Neighborhood in New Bedford, sharing expertise and efficiencies to get the job done. Projects and programs will include:\r\n\r\n Open space development and transformation of brownfields and derelict vacant lots into community assets\r\n\r\n Stewardship, civic pride and celebration\r\n\r\n Youth development through leadership, job readiness and skill building\r\n\r\n Green job training and career development\r\n\r\n Food security and improving access to healthy food through community gardensand farmers markets\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe need for a Groundwork presence in Fall River and New Bedford is abundantly clear; while many nonprofits exist in each community, those organizations are oriented predominantly as service providers to vulnerable and at-risk populations. While a small number of community development corporations exist in the region, they are focused on particular geographies within each community, as opposed to Groundworks eventual citywide scope. There also appears to be lack of an entity to support a more comprehensive project and programmatic response to the intertwined and intractable environmental, economic and social injustices on the ground.\r\n<h2></h2>\r\n&nbsp;','Why Fall River and New Bedford','','inherit','closed','closed','','33-revision-v1','','','2017-06-01 01:55:03','2017-06-01 01:55:03','',33,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/33-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(38,3,'2017-06-01 01:55:49','2017-06-01 01:55:49','&nbsp;\r\n<h2>MISSION STATEMENT</h2>\r\nThe mission of Groundwork Southcoast(GWSC) is to bring about the sustained regeneration, improvement and management of the physical environment by developing community-based partnerships that empower people, businesses and organizations to promote environmental, economic and social well-being.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<h2>OUR ROLE</h2>\r\nGWSC is part of the <a href=\"http://groundworkusa.org/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\"><strong>Groundwork USA</strong></a> network of independent, not-for-profit, environmental organizationscalled Groundwork Trusts. Locally organized and controlled, Groundwork Trusts provide services focused on improving their communities environment, economy, and quality of life.\r\n\r\nEach Trust represents a strong partnership between government, business, foundations, community groups, and residents. Projects serve a common agenda and are designed to accomplish other goals, such as stewarding urban waterways, brown field reclamation, job training and environmental education. All projects and activities of Groundwork are carried out to leverage resources forresidents totransform their own communities.\r\n<h2></h2>','Mission Statement','','inherit','closed','closed','','27-revision-v1','','','2017-06-01 01:55:49','2017-06-01 01:55:49','',27,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/27-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(39,3,'2017-06-01 01:56:38','2017-06-01 01:56:38','<h2>STAFF</h2>\r\nExecutive Director:\r\n\r\nMaura Ramsey\r\n\r\n<span id=\"yui_3_16_0_ym19_1_1496281380157_3214\">Maura has been with GWSC since March 2017. Sheis extremely passionate about furthering social, economic, racial, and environmental justice in our society through community focused leadership development. Prior to accepting the Executive Director position with GWSC, Maura worked at Mother\'s Out Front as the Massachusetts Lead Organizer, a non-profit that works to mobilize mothers, grandmothers and caregivers to have their voices heard as they advocate for a healthy climate for their children. She was also the Director of the South Street Youth Center, a non-profit located on the premises of a Boston Housing Authority development where she developed all programming and outreach to expand the youth center from one</span><span id=\"yui_3_16_0_ym19_1_1496281380157_3221\">small drop-in program to a multi-service space that engaged, residents, neighbors, non-profits, city programs and state based stakeholder to respond to create the changes the community wanted.</span>\r\n<h2>BOARD</h2>\r\nChair:\r\n\r\nMike Coughlin\r\n\r\nVice Chair:\r\n\r\nRay Holberger\r\n\r\nSecretary:\r\n\r\nEric Andrade\r\n\r\nTreasurer:\r\n\r\nBrian Pastori\r\n\r\nMembers:\r\n\r\nJan De Silva\r\n\r\nAmy Blanchette','Staff and Board','','inherit','closed','closed','','22-revision-v1','','','2017-06-01 01:56:38','2017-06-01 01:56:38','',22,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/22-revision-v1',0,'revision',