:26','2017-06-03 16:39:26','','IMG_0527','','inherit','open','closed','','img_0527','','','2017-06-03 16:39:26','2017-06-03 16:39:26','',4,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/wp/../sites/groundworksouth/uploads/2017/05/IMG_0527.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(167,8,'2017-06-03 16:42:05','0000-00-00 00:00:00','{\n    \"bb-theme::fl-footer-bg-opacity\": {\n        \"value\": \"100\",\n        \"type\": \"theme_mod\",\n        \"user_id\": 8\n    }\n}','','','auto-draft','closed','closed','','62d3c42d-5f71-4cbc-8b32-577f6b4aff4a','','','2017-06-03 16:42:05','0000-00-00 00:00:00','',0,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/?p=167',0,'customize_changeset','',0),(168,8,'2017-06-03 16:45:45','2017-06-03 16:45:45','{\n    \"bb-theme::fl-nav-font-size\": {\n        \"value\": \"20\",\n        \"type\": \"theme_mod\",\n        \"user_id\": 8\n    },\n    \"bb-theme::fl-nav-item-spacing\": {\n        \"value\": \"12\",\n        \"type\": \"theme_mod\",\n        \"user_id\": 8\n    },\n    \"bb-theme::fl-header-nav-search\": {\n        \"value\": \"hidden\",\n        \"type\": \"theme_mod\",\n        \"user_id\": 8\n    },\n    \"bb-theme::fl-mobile-nav-toggle\": {\n        \"value\": \"icon\",\n        \"type\": \"theme_mod\",\n        \"user_id\": 8\n    },\n    \"bb-theme::fl-nav-font-format\": {\n        \"value\": \"capitalize\",\n        \"type\": \"theme_mod\",\n        \"user_id\": 8\n    },\n    \"bb-theme::fl-footer-col1-text\": {\n        \"value\": \"Place holder text 1\\n<br />\\nPlace holder text 2\\n<br />\\nPlace holder text 3\",\n        \"type\": \"theme_mod\",\n        \"user_id\": 8\n    }\n}','','','trash','closed','closed','','685bd636-720c-46c4-ba7d-38920093d071','','','2017-06-03 16:45:45','2017-06-03 16:45:45','',0,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/?p=168',0,'customize_changeset','',0),(169,8,'2017-06-03 17:15:31','2017-06-03 17:15:31','<h1>\n		Changing Places. Changing Lives.\n	</h1>\n			<a href=\"#\" target=\"_self\" role=\"button\">\n							Start Here\n					</a>\n	<h3 style=\"text-align: left;\">The mission of Groundwork Southcoast(GWSC) is to bring about the sustained regeneration, improvement and management of the physical environment by developing community-based partnerships that empower people, businesses and organizations to promote environmental, economic and social well-being.</h3>\n	<h5 id=\"yui_3_17_2_1_1496467459506_271\" style=\"text-align: center;\">GROUNDWORK SOUTHCOASTIS A NONPROFIT ORGANIZATION WHOSE WORK</h5>\n<h5 style=\"text-align: center;\">REFLECTS THE OBJECTIVES OF OUR NATIONAL ORGANIZATION GROUNDWORK USA.</h5>\n				<a href=\"#\" target=\"_self\" itemprop=\"url\">\n				<img src=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/uploads/2017/05/14352573_1248273801890087_1117782031678407285_o.jpg\" alt=\"\" itemprop=\"image\"  />\n				</a>\n	<h3><a href=\"#\" target=\"_self\">WHAT WE DO</a></h3>		\n			<p>Find out about Groundwork SouthCoast and the</p>\n<p>results of all our hard work and great partnerships.</p>\n			<a href=\"#\" target=\"_self\" role=\"button\">\n							Learn More\n			</a>\n				<a href=\"#\" target=\"_self\" itemprop=\"url\">\n				<img src=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/uploads/2017/05/12036777_507903089380828_1936469083037503511_n.jpg\" alt=\"\" itemprop=\"image\"  />\n				</a>\n	<h3><a href=\"#\" target=\"_self\">GET INVOVLED</a></h3>		\n			<p style=\"text-align: center;\">Ready to work? Come to one of our many</p>\n<p style=\"text-align: center;\">weekend work days and be ready to get dirty.</p>\n			<a href=\"#\" target=\"_self\" role=\"button\">\n							Find Out How\n			</a>\n	','Home Page','','inherit','closed','closed','','4-revision-v1','','','2017-06-03 17:15:31','2017-06-03 17:15:31','',4,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/4-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(170,8,'2017-06-03 18:05:20','2017-06-03 18:05:20','\n	<h1 style=\"text-align: left;\"><u>STAFF</u></h1>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><img src=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/uploads/2017/06/P24-240x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"240\" height=\"300\" /></p>\n<h3><strong>Executive Director:</strong> Maura Ramsey</h3>\n<p>Maura has been with GWSC since March 2017. Sheis extremely passionate about furthering social, economic, racial, and environmental justice in our society through community focused leadership development. Prior to accepting the Executive Director position with GWSC, Maura worked at Mother\'s Out Front as the Massachusetts Lead Organizer, a non-profit that works to mobilize mothers, grandmothers and caregivers to have their voices heard as they advocate for a healthy climate for their children. She was also the Director of the South Street Youth Center, a non-profit located on the premises of a Boston Housing Authority development where she developed all programming and outreach to expand the youth center from onesmall drop-in program to a multi-service space that engaged, residents, neighbors, non-profits, city programs and state based stakeholder to respond to create the changes the community wanted.</p>\n<h1></h1>\n	<h1 style=\"text-align: left;\"><u>BOARD</u></h1>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><img src=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/uploads/2017/06/me-300x226.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"281\" height=\"212\" /></p>\n<h3><strong>Chair:</strong> Mike Coughlin</h3>\n<p>Michael Coughlin, MS, has been a public health professional at the state and local level since 1992. He is the Outreach and Education Coordinator for Greater Fall River Partners for a Healthier Community and an Adjunct Instructor in Human Services and Psychology at Bristol Community College. He also serves as a Site Visitor for the national Public Health Accreditation Board. Michael retired as the Accreditation Manager in the Office of the Commissioner in the MA Department of Public Health (MDPH) in June 2015. He previously served as the Local Public Health Manager in the Emergency Preparedness Bureau at MDPH. He served as the Director of Health and Human Services for the City of Fall River, MA from 2004-2008.</p>\n<h3><strong>Vice Chair:</strong> Ray Holberger</h3>\n<h3><strong>Secretary:</strong> Eric Andrade</h3>\n<p><img src=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/uploads/2017/06/emerging-leader-head-shot-225x300.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" /></p>\n<h3><strong>Treasurer:</strong> Brian Pastori</h3>\n<p>Brian Pastori has lived in New Bedford since 2004 and is a founding board member of Groundwork SouthCoast. Brian is the Deputy Director of the Community Economic Development Center (CEDC). He has worked at the CEDC since 2005 promoting asset development, neighborhood pride, and skill building in New Bedford with a particular focus on the Acushnet Avenue Neighborhood. Brians work is guided by a commitment to social and economic justice with the goal of building toward equity for oppressed communities.</p>\n<h1></h1>\n	<h1 style=\"text-align: left;\"></h1>\n<h1><u>Members:</u></h1>\n<p>Jan De Silva</p>\n<p>Amy Blanchette</p>\n','Staff and Board','','inherit','closed','closed','','22-revision-v1','','','2017-06-03 18:05:20','2017-06-03 18:05:20','',22,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/22-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(171,8,'2017-06-03 18:12:46','2017-06-03 18:12:46','\n	<h1 style=\"text-align: left;\"><u>STAFF</u></h1>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><img src=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/uploads/2017/06/P24-240x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"240\" height=\"300\" /></p>\n<h3><strong>Executive Director:</strong> Maura Ramsey</h3>\n<p>Maura has been with GWSC since March 2017. Sheis extremely passionate about furthering social, economic, racial, and environmental justice in our society through community focused leadership development. Prior to accepting the Executive Director position with GWSC, Maura worked at Mother\'s Out Front as the Massachusetts Lead Organizer, a non-profit that works to mobilize mothers, grandmothers and caregivers to have their voices heard as they advocate for a healthy climate for their children. She was also the Director of the South Street Youth Center, a non-profit located on the premises of a Boston Housing Authority development where she developed all programming and outreach to expand the youth center from onesmall drop-in program to a multi-service space that engaged, residents, neighbors, non-profits, city programs and state based stakeholder to respond to create the changes the community wanted.</p>\n<h1></h1>\n	<h1 style=\"text-align: left;\"><u>BOARD</u></h1>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><img src=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/uploads/2017/06/me-300x226.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"281\" height=\"212\" /></p>\n<h3><strong>Chair:</strong> Mike Coughlin</h3>\n<p>Michael Coughlin, MS, has been a public health professional at the state and local level since 1992. He is the Outreach and Education Coordinator for Greater Fall River Partners for a Healthier Community and an Adjunct Instructor in Human Services and Psychology at Bristol Community College. He also serves as a Site Visitor for the national Public Health Accreditation Board. Michael retired as the Accreditation Manager in the Office of the Commissioner in the MA Department of Public Health (MDPH) in June 2015. He previously served as the Local Public Health Manager in the Emergency Preparedness Bureau at MDPH. He served as the Director of Health and Human Services for the City of Fall River, MA from 2004-2008.</p>\n<h3></h3>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3><strong>Vice Chair:</strong> Ray Holberger</h3>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<h3><strong>Secretary:</strong> Eric Andrade</h3>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><img src=\"http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/uploads/2017/06/emerging-leader-head-shot-225x300.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" /></p>\n<h3><strong>Treasurer:</strong> Brian Pastori</h3>\n<p>Brian Pastori has lived in New Bedford since 2004 and is a founding board member of Groundwork SouthCoast. Brian is the Deputy Director of the Community Economic Development Center (CEDC). He has worked at the CEDC since 2005 promoting asset development, neighborhood pride, and skill building in New Bedford with a particular focus on the Acushnet Avenue Neighborhood. Brians work is guided by a commitment to social and economic justice with the goal of building toward equity for oppressed communities.</p>\n<h1></h1>\n	<h1 style=\"text-align: left;\"></h1>\n<h1><u>Members:</u></h1>\n<p>Jan De Silva</p>\n<p>Amy Blanchette</p>\n','Staff and Board','','inherit','closed','closed','','22-revision-v1','','','2017-06-03 18:12:46','2017-06-03 18:12:46','',22,'http://groundworksouth.48in48sites.org/22-revision-v1',0,'revision','',0),(172,8,'2017-06-03 18:18:20','2017-06-03 18:18:20','<u><h2>Why Fall River and New Bedford</h2></u>\nGroundwork Southcoast\'s positioning statement, which indicates thespecific ways that mission statement will be implemented on the ground in Fall River and New Bedford, is:\n\nGroundwork Southcoast will collaborate with neighborhoods in Fall River and New Bedford to engage communities in the improvement and stewardship of parks, recreation and conserved natural areas, generate community pride, foster safer and healthier communities; and build diverse partnerships with residents and local businesses to direct and achieve these goals. Groundwork will begin this work with the Flint Neighborhood in Fall River and the Acushnet Avenue Neighborhood in New Bedford, sharing expertise and efficiencies to get the job done. Projects and programs will include:\n\n      Open space development and transformation of brownfields and derelict vacant lots into \n       community assets\n\n      Stewardship, civic pride and celebration\n\n      Youth development through leadership, job readiness and skill building\n\n      Green job training and career development\n\n      Food security and improving access to healthy food through community gardensand farmers \n       markets\n\n&nbsp;\n\nThe need for a Groundwork presence in Fall River and New Bedford is abundantly clear; while many nonprofi